Merge pull request #437 from jonseymour/issue-436-exitcode-regression

Revert "resolves an issue that causes a race condition"

Ensures that callback is called on nextTick(), rather than immediately.

This is required to restore the semantics of one part of
the change from #406 that was preserved in this PR.

Signed-off-by: Jon Seymour <jon@wildducktheories.com>

Revert "resolves an issue that causes a race condition"

This reverts commit 992b8012c4b0734388c6487c556f54d6151a8bea by partially
undoing some (but not all) of the changes made by that commit.

The problem this reversion addresses is that, as of 3.3.8, elasticdump no longer sets a
non-zero status code when a failure occrrs during the dump phase.


Specifically:

elasticdump --input https://nonentity.example/temp --output /tmp/temp.json
echo $?

reports 0 when it should report 1.

The apparent reason for this is that the callback passed in the mainline now returns
a function that calls process.exit(1) instead of performing the call itself.

Since no other changes were made to ensure that the function returned by the
call was actually called process.exit(1) was never called, meaning that
elasticdump could fail failed silently (at least as far as the exit code was concerned).

One part of the original change has been left as is, since it seemed sound, specifically:

https://github.com/taskrabbit/elasticsearch-dump/commit/992b8012c4b0734388c6487c556f54d6151a8bea#diff-f60b04ac83f174b93b06625be32a86f5

Signed-off-by: Jon Seymour <jon@wildducktheories.com>

 Support scroll-requests on AWS ElasticSearch

Support scroll-requests on AWS ElasticSearch

> To avoid a problem with = characters in scroll_id values, use the
> request body, not the query string, to pass scroll_id values to Amazon
> ES.
> ([Source](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticsearch-service/latest/developerguide/aes-supported-es-operations.html))

This change ensures the `scroll_id` is submitted properly on AWS and the
scroll request will not fail with `{"message":null}`.

Signed-off-by: Knut Ahlers <knut@ahlers.me>

`--ignoreType` allows a type to be ignored from the dump/load. Three options are supported. `data,mapping,analyzer`.
Multi-type support is available, when used each type must be comma(,)-separated
`interval` allows control over the interval for spawning a dump/load for a new index.
For small indices this can be set to `0` to reduce delays and optimize performance

transport/elasticsearc: prototype.setMapping: fix loop and callback logic

In this prototype, we sent a put request to ensure the index exists for each
mapping, so I put the rquest.put earlier in the prototype to do this request
only once.  It also ensure that the variable of the callback for putting the
mapping are defined in a function context, so local to that function.

This change also prevent falling into the known case of function declaration
within loops: https://jslinterrors.com/dont-make-functions-within-a-loop
